The Federal Government has flagged off the dissemination of Omega Visitec CD4 rapid test kit laboratory evaluation report. Speaking at the event yesterday in Abuja, the minister of health, Dr. Osagie Ehanire, said the purpose of CD4 estimation in people living with HIV/AIDS is not only to reflect the effectiveness of the therapy with ART but also to identify people who might be vulnerable to opportunistic infections. He said: “The need to identify people with low CD4 count becomes imperative. We therefore define sensitivity as the ability of the test to correctly identify low levels of CD4 counts. “Conversely, specificity becomes the ability of the test device to correctly classify higher CD4 count levels in persons who are not prone to opportunistic infections.” According to him, the Federal Ministry of Health, in 2019, approved the conduct of the Evaluation of Omega Visitect CD4 rapid test kit. Ehanire further stated that the result of the evaluation showed that the test device performed well in identifying persons with low CD4 counts of <350cells/µl with a sensitivity of 97.9 per cent (95%Cl, 96.0-98.9%). He however, stated that the Kit’s ability to detect higher CD4 counts is poor with a specificity of 46.4 per cent (95%Cl, 41.6-51.3%). He therefore recommended it for use in the National HIV testing algorithm.  On the possibility of producing the test kit locally, the Nigerian Representative, Omega Diagnostics ltd, Alhaji Majekodunmi Aborode, said that was part  of agreement reached before the technology was introduced into the country.  “l introduced this technology to our country and I don’t want a situation whereby they will bring this premium product to this country, they will make money and then run away. That era is gone. We know that they are capitalists, but these people are capitalists with a human face,” he explained.